The fermentation of oleaginous yeast has attracted attention for the production of various oils. Oleaginous yeast is a unique type of yeast that contains abundant lipid droplets in cells. Lipomyces starkeyi, Yarrowia lipolytica, and Rhodosporidium toruloides can accumulate neutral lipids that typically exceed \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$20\%$$\end{document}20% of the dry cell weight and approach \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$70\%$$\end{document}70% of the dry cell weight in some cases. These yeasts can convert renewable and waste-derived feedstocks into single-cell oils that are relevant to biodiesel, oleochemicals, and food (Abeln and Chuck 2021). In particular, L. starkeyi can accumulate high triacylglycerol (often exceeding \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$60\%$$\end{document}60% of the dry cell weight) with the ability to utilize mixed sugars (e.g., glucose and xylose) from lignocellulosic hydrolysates (McNeil and Stuart 2018). Therefore, culturing L. starkeyi is an important route to high oil production (Kitahara et al 2023; Sutanto et al 2018; Takaku et al 2021, 2020; Ohtomo et al 2023; Nagatsu et al 2024).

