With respect to lipid dynamics, upon glucose depletion (Fig. 7b), the bulk lipid content declined (Fig. 7a). At the single-cell level, the distributions of the lipid droplet area and the oil content shifted toward lower values while remaining broad (Figs. 8b and c), indicating pronounced cell-to-cell heterogeneity superimposed on a population-level decline. This pattern supports the interpretation that storage triacylglycerol is mobilized under carbon starvation and is consistent with established yeast physiology. Specifically, neutral lipids accumulate under conditions of nitrogen limitation. In contrast, when the carbon source is exhausted, storage triacylglycerol is utilized via pathways that include lipophagy and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\beta $$\end{document}β-oxidation (van Zutphen et al 2014; Pomraning et al 2019). Thus, the widespread across cells reflects heterogeneity in lipid synthesis capacity, even though the overall trend is a net decrease in cellular lipid. Because our method is completely non-invasive, we can track the growth status of each cell over the cultivation time. These results confirm the insufficiency of conventional methods that can only detect entire cells and the necessity of our method because it can detect lipid droplets within cells.

